gmd:abstract.gco:CharacterString:
The Bureau of Meteorology issues Severe Weather Warnings whenever severe weather is occurring in an area or is expected to develop or move into an area. The warnings describe the area under threat and the expected hazards. Warnings are issued with varying lead-times, depending on the weather situation, and range from just an hour or two up to about 24 hours. Severe Weather Warnings are issued for:

Sustained winds of gale force (63 km/h) or more - damaging winds;
Wind gusts of 90 km/h or more (100 km/h or more in Tasmania) - destructive winds;
Very heavy rain that may lead to flash flooding; 
Abnormally high tides (or storm tides) expected to exceed highest astronomical tide;
Unusually large surf waves expected to cause dangerous conditions on the coast - damaging surf or dangerous surf (Qld). NB High tides are not issued for Vic and parts of SA and damaging surf are not issued for Vic, Tas and SA.

The state ratings have been combined into a national product for Web Map Service and Web Feature Service layers.

